Ri referred to the joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first US sitting president and North Korean leader summit in Singapore on June 12, in a statement that Kim assured of "the disarmament of the Korean peninsula from nuclear weapons" and Trump promised to guarantee North Korea's security.
North Korea has made efforts to officially end the 1950-1953 Korean War, but the United States has insisted that Pyongyang must first abandon its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed the facilitation of strict international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
"The United States is calling for 'removal of nuclear weapons first', and have increased pressure through sanctions to achieve their goals by force — even resisting a 'proclamation of peace'," Ri said.
"The notion that sanctions would bring us to our knees is a wish of the indifferent.
But the problem is that the constant sanctions only deepen our distrust."
Ri did not mention plans to hold the next Kim-Trump summit, which Trump himself stressed to the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister stressed three meetings with South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: "If the party requiring disarmament were South Korea and not the United States, the situation would not have reached such a dead end."
Yet Rin's tone was significantly different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that heading missiles towards the United States in continental areas was inevitable after "bad president" Trump called Kim a "missile man" with suicidal intentions.
Last year, Trump threatened to " completely destroy" North Korea. However, this year Trump praised Kim profusely for his courage to approach the abandonment of weapons, but stressed that there is still much work to be done and sanctions must remain until North Korea renounces nuclear weapons.
