Harvard students complete a course of adequate rest
All undergraduate students at Harvard University will attend a course this year to increase student rest. The course is a counterattack to the university's thriving macho culture, where students weigh long nights with the power of caffeine.
According to the researcher, students at the best university in the world are often quite unaware of the basics of their own well-being.
Charles Czeisler, a professor at Harvard University School of Medicine who works in sleep research at Brigham and Women's Hospital, believes the course is the first of its kind in the United States.
Czeisler had an idea for the course after lecturing on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"After the lecture, a young woman came to me and said, 'Why do I only hear about it now, in my last year of study?'
No one had ever told him about the need for sleep, which I found surprising," he told the Telegraph in an interview.
For the first time this year, the course will guide students on how to support academic and athletic performance and improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor at Harvard University School of Medicine and deputy director of health services at the university, says the university ended up organizing the course after hearing how students suffered severe sleep deprivation during the week of study.
The hour-long course includes a set of interactive tasks.
One section shows students a picture of a dormitory room where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports equipment and books, thus gaining information about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of sleep deprivation on sports performance and the importance of regular evening activities.
The second section will tell participants how long-term sleep deprivation can raise the risks of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routines.
"We know this has no immediate impact on students' behavior.
However, we believe they have a right to know about these issues in exactly the same way they have the right to know about the health effects of smoking," Professor Czeisler adds.
According to Professor Czeisler, all-night study marathons are still a subject of pride, and modern technology and the ever-increasing pressures of students made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
"Getting enough and high-quality sleep should be a 'secret weapon' for students against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, and even against weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes a state similar to starvation in the brain, which is why a person is constantly hungry," the professor points out.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student of chemical and physical psychology in California, helped Professor Czeisler plan the course after attending one of the courses he taught in his first year at Harvard last year.
He says the course opened his eyes and gave impetus to organizing a course covering all campus students.
He hopes that all graduate students can complete a similar study module before moving to a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students set an alarm clock to remind them of bedtime in addition to waking up in the morning and urges them to keep in mind the adverse effects of electronic display devices and LED lighting on the circadian rhythm, which can make it difficult to fall asleep.
