Almanac: Geigermeter inventor
Next, page "Sunday Morning" from our almanac: September 30, 1882. Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger, a future physicist, was born in Germany today 136 years ago.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, which later led to the development of a device known as a geiger meter.
The method became one of the pillars of science, and also a central concept of pop culture. For example, the 1950 film "Coronado Watches", in which Roy Rogers and Dale Evans present scientists who seem quite cowboys:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: "It's a geigermeter, used to search for radioactive minerals such as uranium.
When you place your headphones on your ears, you can actually hear the effect of radioactive radiation on minerals."
Evans: "Look, it's really a ride!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945 a few days before his 63rd birthday.
However, the invention that bears his name still lives on.
New cancer vaccine capable of teaching immune system to ‘see’ malignant cells
New cancer vaccine is capable of teaching the immune system to ‘see’ malignant cells and destroy them
Vaccine teaches immune system to identify malignant cells as part of treatment
The method isolates resistant cells from the patient and changes them in the laboratory
After treatment, cells injected back into the body are able to ‘see’ proteins typical of multiple cancers
Koerokote has given promising results in different patients with cancer.
For example, cancer cells in a patient with ovarian cancer disappeared within 18 months after being treated with a vaccine that teaches the immune system to identify malignant cells.
The method isolates resistant cells from the patient and changes them in the laboratory so that they are able to ‘see' the HER2 proteins typical of several cancers.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, USA, describes the method: "Based on our results, it's a very promising vaccine."
HER2 "directs the growth of several types of cancer," Professor Berzofsky explains. "These include breast cancer and ovarian, lung and colon cancers."
A similar approach — taking resistant cells from a patient and teaching them to attack cancer cells — has also produced results in the treatment of a type of leukemia.
